ambda${\textless}/em{\textgreater} and {\textless}em{\textgreater}$\kappa${\textless}/em{\textgreater} is independent of pressure and is controlled by nearly constant thermal expansion coefficient with increasing temperature. Smaller {\textless}em{\textgreater}$\lambda${\textless}/em{\textgreater} of olivine aggregate with high Fe content would produce a warmer mantle and, in turn, possibly a thicker crust in the Fe-rich Mars, while heat in the Fe-poor Mercury can escape faster than the other terrestrial planets. Olivine-dominant asteroids with high Fe concentration could have longer cooling history and lower thermal inertia on the surface.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
